#Text=[0069] Table IX shows fuel properties of sample diesels produced by Example 2.
#Text=The NOISE analysis of the diesel fraction indicates that it is mainly composed of paraffins, iso-paraffins, and naphthenes, as shown in Table IX.
#Text=The amount of naphthenes in hydrocondensation diesel is twice the amount in ULSD, the amount of paraffins is 1/5, and aromatics are 1/10 of the amount in ULSD.
#Text=This unique product distribution resulted in excellent cold flow properties compared to ULSD.
#Text=The cloud point and pour point of the distillate fraction were -66 and -70.degree.
#Text=F. indicating that this biomass based diesel fuel may be used at or below 60.degree.
#Text=F.
#Text=The cetane number of the hydrodeoxygenation-diesel measured through a blended IQT test is .about.58, superior to conventional ULSD.
#Text=Other properties such as density, API gravity, lubricity, heat of combustion, and total acid number (TAN) are similar to that of ULSD.
#Text=The distillation profile (T10, T50, and T90 points) also resembles that of ULSD.
#Text=Furthermore, the amount of sulfur is <1 ppm.
#Text=This superior quality on-spec diesel can be directly blended into the existing ULSD pool as a drop in fuel.
#Text=The measured flash, pour and cloud point of distillate fraction are superior to that of ULSD.
